The '''Jeepster''' is an [[automobile]] originally produced by [[Willys|Willys-Overland Motors]] from 1948 to 1950.{{Sfn|Mattar|2012}} It was developed in hopes of filling a gap in the company's product line, crossing over from their "utilitarian" proto [[SUV]]s and trucks to the passenger automobile market. The basic model included numerous deluxe features and interior fittings in addition to a high level of standard equipment that cost extra on other automobiles.  A total of almost 20,000 were manufactured.

The Jeepster name was revived in 1966 on a new model, the C-101 '''[[Jeepster Commando]]'''. [[American Motors]] (AMC), [[Willys|Willys-Overland]]'s successor, removed Jeepster from the name for 1972, ending production after 1973.

==Background==
After [[World War II]], [[Jeep]] trademark owner, Willys, began producing and marketing the "CJ" (for Civilian Jeep) to farmers, foresters, and others with similar utilitarian needs. It also began producing [[Willys Jeep Station Wagon|the Jeep Wagon/Panel Utility/Pick-up]] in 1946,{{Sfn|Brown|1994|pp=70, 72}} and the [[Willys Jeep Truck|Jeep Truck]] in 1947.{{Sfn|Brown|1994|p=74}}

Seeing a gap in their product lineup, Willys developed the Jeepster to crossover from their "utilitarian" trucks to the passenger automobile market. Willys-Overland lacked the machinery to form deep-drawn fenders or complicated shapes, so the vehicle had to use a simple and slab-sided design.{{Sfn|Brown|1994|pp=58, 68}}<ref name="development" /> Industrial designer [[Brooks Stevens]] styled a line of postwar vehicles for Willys using a common [[automobile platform|platform]] that included the Jeep pickup and station wagon, as well as a sporty two-door open car<ref name="development"/> that he envisioned as a sports car for veterans of World War II.{{Sfn|Mattar|2012}}

The Willys-Overland Jeepster ("VJ" internally) was introduced in April 1948,{{Sfn|Brown|1994|p=76}} and produced through 1950.{{Sfn|Brown|1994|p=78}} Some leftover models were sold under the 1951 [[model year]].{{Sfn|Brown|1994|p=78}}{{Sfn|Statham|2002|p=77}}

==1948==
[[File:1948 Willys Jeepster.jpg|thumb|250px|1948 Willys Jeepster.]]
[[File:1949 Willys Overland Jeepster (28971691904).jpg|thumb|250px|1949 Jeepster rear with continental kit]]
The basic 1948 Jeepster included numerous deluxe features and interior fittings in addition to a high level of standard equipment that cost extra on other automobiles. These included, among many others, [[whitewall tires]], [[hubcap]]s with bright trim rings, [[sun visor]]s, deluxe steering wheel, wind wings, locking glovebox, cigar lighter, and [[continental tire]] with fabric cover.<ref>[[#HSW48 51J p4|1948 Willys Jeepster Design Features]]</ref> The Jeepster had Willys' World War II-proven {{convert|134.2|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} [[inline-four engine|straight-4]] "[[Willys Go Devil engine|Go Devil]]" engine, and plastic side curtains, but its $1,765 price was about the same as a Ford Super DeLuxe club convertible with roll-down windows, fancier styling, and a [[V8 engine]].{{Sfn|Mattar|2012}}

The car was only offered with [[rear-wheel drive]], thus limiting its appeal with other Jeep customers.{{Sfn|Brown|1994|p=78}} Its distinctive boxy styling and performance were praised by automotive journalists.{{Citation needed|date= January 2015}} However, the Jeepster did not catch on with the intended [[market segmentation|market segment]]. Sales were also limited by sparse advertising and an insufficient dealer network.<ref>[[#HSW48 51J p5|1948 Willys Jeepster Reviews]]</ref>

The Jeepster's engine gave {{convert|63|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}, which was coupled to a 3-speed [[manual transmission]] with standard [[overdrive (mechanics)|overdrive]].<ref name="intro" /> The Planadyne single transverse leaf spring independent front suspension , entire drivetrain, front end, rear suspension, steering, and four-wheel [[drum brake]]s were from the [[Willys Jeep Wagon|Willys Station Wagon]].<ref name="intro" />{{Sfn|Brown|1994|pp=68,70,76}} The flat-topped rear fenders were taken from the Jeep truck line.{{Sfn|Brown|1994|p=76}}

==1949==
The 1949 Jeepster began production with a one-model/one-engine offering. The price was lowered to $1,495, with some previously standard features returning as extra-cost options. Toward the middle of the year, an additional model was introduced, the VJ3-6, powered by Willys' new ''[[Willys Lightning engine|L148 Lightning]]'' six-cylinder engine.<ref name=49to50 />

==1950==
The 1950 model year saw the VJ-3 Jeepster's first styling revisions, which included a new instrument panel and redesigned front end featuring a V-shaped grille with horizontal chrome trim.{{Sfn|Statham|2002|p=77}} The car had very little standard equipment.{{cn|date=August 2017}} Willys' ''[[Willys Lightning engine|L161 Lightning]]'' six-cylinder was offered in addition to the standard ''Go Devil'' four-cylinder.<ref name=49to50 /> Model designations were dependent on production timeframe, with early 1950s four-cylinder Jeepsters given VJ-3 463 and six-cylinders VJ-3 663, changed to VJ-473 and VJ-673, respectively, for later year vehicles.<ref name=49to50 />

==Engines==
* 1948-1950 - ''[[Willys Go Devil engine|L134 Go Devil]]'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] — {{Convert|134.1|cuin|cc|abbr=on}}{{Sfn|Mattar|2012}}
* 1949-1950 - ''[[Willys Lightning engine|L148 Lightning]]'' [[Straight-six engine|I6]] —{{Convert|148.5|cuin|cc|abbr=on}}{{Sfn|Mattar|2012}}
* 1950 - ''[[Willys Hurricane engine|F134 Hurricane]]'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] —{{Convert|134.2|cuin|cc|abbr=on}}{{Sfn|Mattar|2012}}
* 1950 - ''[[Willys Lightning engine|L161 Lightning]]'' [[Straight-six engine|I6]] —{{Convert|161|cuin|cc|abbr=on}}{{Sfn|Mattar|2012}}

==Production==
A total of 19,132 original VJ Jeepsters were produced over three model years:{{Sfn|Mattar|2012}} 
* 1948 - 10,326
* 1949 - 2,960
* 1950 - 5,836

