{{Short description|Line of American vehicles sold by Jeep under various vehicle classes}}
{{about|Jeep Cherokee line dating to 1974|luxury SUV line dating to 1993|Jeep Grand Cherokee}}
{{Other uses}}
{{Infobox automobile
| name        = Jeep Cherokee
| image       = 2019 Jeep Cherokee Latitude front 5.27.18.jpg
|caption      = Fifth generation (KL)
|manufacturer=[[American Motors]] (1974-1987)<br>[[Chrysler Corporation]] (1988-1998)<br>[[DaimlerChrysler]] (1999-2001)<br>[[Chrysler Corporation|Chrysler Group LLC]] (2013-2014)<br>[[FCA US LLC]] (2015-present)
| model_years  = 1974-present
| class        = [[Sport utility vehicle|Full-size SUV]] (1974–1983)<br>[[Compact sport utility vehicle|Compact SUV]] (1984-2012)<br>[[crossover SUV|Compact crossover SUV]] (2013-present)
| layout         = [[Front-engine design|Front engine]], [[rear-wheel drive]] (1974–2013)<br>[[Front-engine, front-wheel-drive layout|Front-engine, front-wheel drive]] (2013–present)<br>[[Front-engine, four-wheel-drive layout|Front-engine, four-wheel drive]] (1974–present)
}}
The '''Jeep Cherokee''' is a line of [[United States|American]] vehicles sold by [[Jeep]] under various vehicle classes. Originally sold as a variant of the popular [[Jeep Wagoneer (SJ)|Jeep Wagoneer]], the Cherokee has evolved from a full-size [[Sport utility vehicle|SUV]] to one of the first [[Compact sport utility vehicle|compact SUVs]] and eventually into its current incarnation as a [[Crossover (automobile)|crossover SUV]]. The nameplate has been in continuous use in some form since 1974 and also spawned Jeep's most successful vehicle, the [[Jeep Grand Cherokee]], which was originally slated to be part of the Cherokee's lineup. The vehicle is named after the [[Cherokee]] tribe of [[Native Americans in the United States|North American Indians]].
__TOC__
{{clear}}

==First generation (SJ)==
{{see also|Jeep Cherokee (SJ)}}
[[File:1974 Jeep Cherokee S - Beach (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|1974 Jeep Cherokee S (US)]]
The Cherokee was a rebadged reintroduction of a two-door body style [[Jeep Wagoneer (SJ)|Jeep Wagoneer]], with a redesigned [[greenhouse (car)|greenhouse]] that eliminated the car's [[Pillar (car)|C-pillar]]. Instead the Cherokee sported a much wider D-pillar and a single, long fixed rear side window with an optional flip-out section. Previously, a two-door version had been available in the Jeep Wagoneer line (from 1963 to 1967), although this had the same [[Pillar (car)|pillar]] and window configuration as the four-door Wagoneer. The Cherokee replaced the [[Jeepster Commando]], whose sales had not met expectations despite an extensive 1972 revamp. The Cherokee appealed to a younger market than the Wagoneer, which was regarded more as a family SUV.

The Cherokee was marketed as the "sporty" two-door variant of Jeep's [[station wagon]]. The term "sport(s) utility vehicle" appears for the first time in the 1974 Cherokee sales brochure.<ref name=74Jeeppage>{{cite web |url=https://www.autopaper.com/images/2214/98959-02.jpg |title=1974 model year Jeep brochure picture – Cherokee page |publisher=Jeep |location=US |year=1973 |access-date=4 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=74Jeepfront>{{cite web |url=http://www.lov2xlr8.no/brochures/jeep/74jeep.html |title=1974 model year Jeep Cherokee brochure – front |publisher=Jeep |location=US |year=1973 |access-date=4 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Allen |first=Jim |title=Jeep: Collector's Library |publisher=Motorbooks, MBI Publishing | year=2003 |page=168 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=4ywrhvzRCsEC&pg=PA168&dq=term+Sport+Utility+appears+for+the+first+time+1974 |isbn= 978-0-7603-1486-9 |accessdate= September 2013 |authorlink=Jim Allen (4x4 writer)}}</ref> A four-door was not added to the lineup until 1977. Other than the base model, the [[car model|trim level]]s of the Cherokee included the S (Sport), Chief, Golden Eagle, Golden Hawk, Limited, Classic, Sport, Pioneer, and Laredo.
{{Clear}}

==Second generation (XJ)==
{{see also|Jeep Cherokee (XJ)}}
[[File:Jeep Cherokee 2-door.jpg|thumb|right|1984– 2001 Jeep Cherokee 2-door]]
While the Wagoneer continued in production for another eight years as the Grand Wagoneer, the Cherokee nameplate was moved to a new platform for 1984. Without a traditional [[body-on-frame]] chassis, the Cherokee instead featured a light-weight [[unibody]] design.<ref name=Allpar>{{cite web|title=Jeep Cherokee, the best of breed SUV: 1975-2001 |url= http://www.allpar.com/trucks/jeep/cherokee.html |website=Allpar |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>

This generation Cherokee would eventually be well-known as an innovator of the modern SUV, as it spawned competitors as other automakers began to notice that this Jeep design began replacing regular cars.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bradsher |first=Keith |title=High and Mighty: SUVs&nbsp;— the World's Most Dangerous Vehicles and How They Got That Way |publisher=PublicAffairs |year=2002 |isbn=978-1-58648-123-0 |page=[https://archive.org/details/highmightysuvs00brad/page/41 41] |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/highmightysuvs00brad/page/41 }}</ref> It also began to supplant the role of the station wagon and "transformed from truck to limousine in the eyes of countless suburban owners."<ref name="Cumberford">{{cite journal| url= http://www.automobilemag.com/features/lists/0604_jeep_cherokee/ |first=Robert |last=Cumberford |title=20 greatest cars |journal=Automobile Magazine |quote=Great designs never grow old, a truth no better confirmed than by designer Dick Teague's masterpiece, the Jeep Cherokee. Possibly the best SUV shape of all time, it is the paradigmatic model to which other designers have since aspired. |date=April 2009 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> The XJ is a "significant link in the evolution of the 4x4."<ref name="Brubaker107">{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=QKrYGfVMUdMC&pg=PA107&lpg=PA107&dq=vehicle+is+noteworthy+as+the+first+nonmilitary+4x4+with+unibody+construction |page=107 |title=Jeep Off-Road |first=Ken |last=Brubaker |first2=Tom |last2=Morr |publisher=Motorbooks |year=2007 |isbn=978-0760329948 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>

It would prove to be so popular that the second generation Cherokee's replacement was released as a separate vehicle altogether as the [[Jeep Grand Cherokee]], itself starting a successive line of vehicles as Jeep's flagship vehicle.

{{Clear}}

==Third generation (KJ)==
{{see also|Jeep Liberty (KJ)}}
[[File:2003 Jeep Cherokee (KJ MY03) Limited Edition wagon (2015-07-09) 01.jpg|thumb|right|2003 Jeep Cherokee Limited Edition wagon (Australia)]]
The third generation, marketed as the '''[[Jeep Liberty]]''' in [[North America]] to differentiate it from the Grand Cherokee, was introduced in April 2001 for the 2002 model year. It was sold as the Jeep Cherokee in markets outside of North America.

The Cherokee was priced between the [[Jeep Wrangler|Wrangler]] and Grand Cherokee. It remained the smallest of the 4-door Jeep SUVs up until the crossover-based 4-door [[Jeep Compass|Compass]] and [[Jeep Patriot|Patriot]] arrived for 2007. The Cherokee featured unibody-construction. It was assembled at the [[Toledo North Assembly Plant]] in the United States, as well as in other countries including Egypt and Venezuela.

It was the first Jeep vehicle to use [[rack and pinion]] steering.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allpar.com/model/jeep/liberty.html |title=Jeep Liberty Steering |publisher=Allpar.com |date=2005-05-15 |accessdate=2010-09-29}}</ref> It was also the first Jeep to use the two then-new ''[[Chrysler PowerTech engine|PowerTech]]'' engines; the {{convert|150|hp}} 2.4 [[Liter|L]] [[straight-4]], which was discontinued in 2006, and the {{convert|210|hp}} 3.7 L [[V6]]. However, the Cherokee was not the first Jeep vehicle to use an [[independent front suspension]], as the Wagoneer first used it in the 1963 model. But, that independent front suspension was limited to four wheel drive versions and, even then, was a short lived option.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wagoneers.com/FSJ/rigs/63_ifs_rice/ALL.html |title=Bruce Rice's 1963 IFS Wagoneer 4x4 |publisher=wagoneers.com |date=2007-12-24 |accessdate=2010-12-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100730040804/http://wagoneers.com/FSJ/rigs/63_ifs_rice/ALL.html |archivedate=2010-07-30 }}</ref>

{{Clear}}

==Fourth generation (KK)==
{{see also|Jeep Liberty (KK)}}
[[File:Jeep Cherokee Liberty 2.8 CRD 2012 (16733352286).jpg|thumb|right|Jeep Cherokee Liberty (US)]]
Still using the Jeep Liberty name in North America, the Cherokee was redesigned in 2008. For the first time, a [[Rebadging|rebadged]] version of a Jeep model existed, as [[Dodge]] sold this version of the Cherokee as the [[Dodge Nitro]] during the same time period as the fourth-generation Cherokee. It was eventually discontinued both due to slow sales as well as [[Sergio Marchionne]] wanting to avoid duplicated vehicles with Dodge and Jeep (as well as [[Chrysler (division)|Chrysler]]) sharing the same sales network.

With the smaller Patriot and Compass now available to cater to MPG-conscious buyers, the four-cylinder engine was dropped from the Cherokee's offerings. The iron-block, aluminium-head [[V6 engine|V6]] was the only engine available for 2008. Towing capacity was {{convert|5000|lb|0}}. Jeep discontinued the Cherokee's [[Common rail diesel|CRD]] for the American market because it couldn't meet tougher 2007 emissions standards for diesel engines. Transmission choices were both carry-overs: a six-speed [[manual transmission|manual]] or a four-speed [[automatic transmission|automatic]]. Standard equipment included electronic stability control with roll mitigation, [[traction control system|traction control]], and [[anti-lock brakes]] with brake assist. New Features included standard side airbags. Optional features are rain-sensing wipers, [[Sirius Satellite Radio]], [[Bluetooth]], a [[navigation system]], and the [[MyGig]] entertainment system, complete with a 30[[Gigabyte|GB]] [[hard drive]].

{{Clear}}

==Fifth generation (KL)==
{{see also|Jeep Cherokee (KL)}}
[[File:2016 Jeep Cherokee Limited Multjet II 2.2.jpg|thumb|right|Jeep Cherokee Limited Multijet (United Kingdom)]]
For the fifth generation, the Cherokee nameplate returned to North America as the vehicle was converted to a crossover and grew to midsize in order to make room for the [[Jeep Renegade (BU)|Jeep Renegade]] below the Cherokee and Compass. It was introduced for the 2014 [[model year]] at the 2013 [[New York International Auto Show]] and the sales started in November 2013.<ref name="NY Daily news">{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/autos/chrysler-lets-2014-jeep-cherokee-details-fly-new-york-auto-show-debut-article-1.1273180|title=Chrysler lets 2014 Jeep Cherokee details fly ahead of New York auto show debut|accessdate=February 27, 2013|work=[[Daily News (New York)]]}}</ref><ref name="Jeep.com" /><ref name="Jeep.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.jeep.com/en/2014/cherokee/|title=The All-New 2014 Jeep Cherokee|accessdate=March 7, 2013|work=[[Jeep]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112184312/http://www.jeep.com/en/2014/cherokee/|archive-date=November 12, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Cherokee is the first Jeep vehicle to be built on the [[Fiat Compact platform|Fiat Compact/Compact U.S. Wide platform]], co-developed by Chrysler and Fiat.<ref name="Autoblog" /> The Jeep Cherokee is built at [[Belvidere Assembly Plant]] in [[Belvidere, Illinois]].<ref name="Forbes" />

The Cherokee has a highway fuel economy rating of {{convert|31|mpgu.s.|L/100 km mpgimp}}<ref name="Autoblog">{{cite web|last=Harley|first=Michael|title=2014 Jeep Cherokee flaunts its new contemporary curves|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2013/03/27/2014-jeep-cherokee-flaunts-its-new-contemporary-curves/|work=autoblog.com|publisher=[[Autoblog.com]]|accessdate=27 March 2013|date=27 March 2013}}</ref> and a 45% better fuel economy rating than the Liberty/Cherokee it replaced.<ref name="Jeep.com" /><ref name="Forbes">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/matthewdepaula/2013/02/26/2014-jeep-cherokee-polarizes-with-new-design/|title=Jeep Revives Cherokee For 2014 With Polarizing New Design|accessdate=February 27, 2013|work=[[Forbes]]}}</ref>

Despite its controversial front-end styling,<ref name="Jeep.com" /><ref name="Forbes"/> the fifth-generation Cherokee would become such a sales success that FCA discontinued the slow-selling [[Dodge Dart (PF)|Dodge Dart]] and [[Chrysler 200]] (both mechanically similar to the Cherokee) in order to increase production capacity for the Cherokee to meet demand.  For 2019 the front end is to be updated to a more conservative style. In 2019, a new 2.0L turbo engine was added to the engine line up. It creates 270 HP and 295 LBS FT of torque. There is also an already existing 3.2L V-6, which is best for towing; and a 2.4L inline-4.

